            "id": "95eb37fba85d4bb78a555",
            "questionText": "A construction manager is calculating the volume of concrete required for a new foundation. The foundation's measured dimensions from a laser distance meter are a length of $!$12.550\\,m$!$, a width of $!$8.200\\,m$!$, and a specified height of $!$0.300\\,m$!$. Note that the laser meter consistently reads $!$5\\,mm$!$ short due to miscalibration. Calculate the corrected volume of concrete needed in cubic meters, ensuring that the systematic error is accounted for and that the final answer is expressed with the correct number of significant figures.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "b6e53a54d9ff4debb7b19",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by considering the effect of the systematic error in the measurements. Identify the correct way to adjust a measured dimension when a consistent error is present.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "8eae554f-89f2-47e3-8d04-053129768b82",
                        "3474184d-fe1b-4c7e-b099-9213ddedc947"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Corrected dimension = measured + error$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Corrected dimension = measured - error$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Corrected dimension = measured \\times error$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "707483b0df574cc59056b",
                    "stepText": "Great, now use the adjustment rule from the previous step to calculate the corrected length. Add the error (in meters) to the measured length $!$12.550\\,m$!$.",
